Preview

What is Dementia?

According to WHO Dementia is a syndrome in which there is deterioration in memory, thinking, behaviour and the ability to perform everyday activities. Although dementia mainly affects older people, it is not a normal part of aging. Alzheimer disease is the most common form of dementia and may contribute to 6070% of cases.

In our project

In our project we try to predict and diagnose Dementia rating using some ML algorithms.

This dataset contain 150 subjects who scanned on two or more visits, separated by at least one year for a total of 373 imaging sessions, and we target the CDR fucntion

CDR is Clinical Dementia Rating (0 = no dementia, 0.5 = very mild AD, 1 = mild and moderate)

Explaining the variables

Subject.ID - Patient ID

MRI.ID - MRI Examination ID

Group (Converted / Demented / Nondemented) - Converted is a person that his diagnosed was changed after the first visit.

Visit - Number of visit

MR.Delay - Delay in days between each MRI examination (contrast)

Demographics Info

M.F - Gender (M if Male, F if Female)

Hand - Handedness(R/L)

Age - Age in years

EDUC - Years of education

SES - Socioeconomic status. 1 is highest status - 5 is the lowest status

Clinical Info

MMSE - Mini-Mental State Examination score (range is from 0 = worst to 30 = best)

CDR - Clinical Dementia Rating (0 = no dementia, 0.5 = very mild AD, 1 = mild AD, 2 = moderate AD)

Derived anatomic volumes

eTIV - Estimated total intracranial volume, mm3

nWBV - Normalized whole-brain volume, expressed as a percent of all voxels in the atlas-masked image that are labeled as gray or white matter by the automated tissue segmentation process

ASF - Atlas scaling factor (unitless). Computed scaling factor that transforms native-space brain and skull to the atlas target (i.e., the determinant of the transform matrix)

ML Classicifation Algorithms

Normalize function

normalize <- function(x) {
return ((x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x)))
}

Normalized data dataframe

n_data <- as.data.frame(lapply(newdata[1:8], normalize))

Preparing data for KNN

Change the target from factor to numeric

KNN doesnt like factor therefore we changed the column to numeric now the new CDR is -

1 = no dementia, 2 = very mild AD, 3 = mild / moderate AD

instead of -

0 = no dementia, 0.5 = very mild AD, 1 = mild / moderate AD

newdata$CDR<-as.numeric(newdata$CDR)

Divide data to train and test sets

ind <- sample(2, nrow(n_data), replace=TRUE, prob=c(0.7,0.3))

test <- n_data[ind==2,]

train_labels <- newdata[ind==1, 9]
test_labels <- newdata[ind==2, 9]

First algorithm - KNN

K=1

table <- data.frame(pred_table$table)

plotTable <- table %>%
  mutate(goodbad = ifelse(table$Prediction == table$Reference, "True", "False")) %>%
  group_by(Reference) %>%
  mutate(prop = Freq/sum(Freq))

  geom_tile() +
  geom_text(aes(label = Freq), vjust = .5, fontface  = "bold", alpha = 1)  +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(True = "green", False = "red")) +

Fifth Algorithm - SVM

ind <- sample(2, nrow(newdata), replace=TRUE, prob=c(0.7,0.3))
svmtrain <- newdata[ind==1,]
svmtest <- newdata[ind==2,]
svm_classifier <- ksvm(CDR ~ ., data = svmtrain, kernel = "vanilladot")
##  Setting default kernel parameters
svm_pred <- predict(svm_classifier, svmtest)
agreement <- svm_pred == svmtest$CDR
table(agreement)
## agreement
## FALSE  TRUE 
##    29    82
svm_classifier2 <- ksvm(CDR ~ ., data = svmtrain, kernel = "rbfdot")
svm_pred2 <- predict(svm_classifier2, svmtest)
agreement <- svm_pred2 == svmtest$CDR
table(agreement)
## agreement
## FALSE  TRUE 
##    34    77

Weve tried 2 SVM models with different kernels, and we can see that vanilladot better gave us better results.

ML Clustering Algorithm

K-Means

Elbow Method

K-Means is an algorithm for unsupervised data, elbow method help to determine how many clusters there are in the data

set.seed(123)

# function to compute total within-cluster sum of square 
wss <- function(k) {
  kmeans(n_data, k, nstart = 10 )$tot.withinss
}

# Compute and plot wss for k = 1 to k = 15
k.values <- 1:15

# extract wss for 2-15 clusters
wss_values <- map_dbl(k.values, wss)

plot(k.values, wss_values,
       type="b", pch = 19, frame = FALSE, 
       xlab="Number of clusters K",
       ylab="Total within-clusters sum of squares")

the elbow method recommand k=4, Weve decided to continue with k=3 because we know that there are 3 groups in our data (3 levels of CDR)

Summary

First lets remember that Dementia is not easy too predict, especially in very mild levels, its a mental issue that not physically visible and has a large scale of levels, makes it hard to determine by doctors and by machine learning.

We can see that the Descision Tree gave us the best results with nearly 87% accuracy, its amazing to see that the first divide in the partitiong was if MMSE value is greater or less than 27, thats correlated to the official grades in this test when grade great than 27 is in no dementia group and less than 27 is in demented group.

other models like svm and rf gave us good results too. the KNN model has around 80% accuracy in k=1 and less in greater k values, maybe our features are too close to each other, without huge difference, and when the KNN try to group bigger groups by Euclidean distance, we get many False results.

With Nave Bayes, we assume that the predictor variables are conditionally independent of one another. maybe in our data is an advantage because most of our features are weakly correlated to the target, therefore the results was the good and pretty similiar for k=1 in KNN.

The results highly depends on the MMSE test while Age, Educational Level and Social-Economic Status have not great influence.
